library(ISLR)

# Given a filename, return the filepath. Default folder is the `data` folder in the current working directory.
get_path <- function(filename) {
  str_c(getwd(), "data", filename, sep = "/")
}

Exercise 9

Auto <- read.csv(get_path("Auto.csv"), na.strings = "?") %>% na.omit()
Auto

  (a)

Identify quantitative variables:

is_numeric_col <- map_lgl(Auto, is.numeric)
names(Auto)[is_numeric_col]
[1] "mpg"          "cylinders"    "displacement" "horsepower"   "weight"       "acceleration" "year"         "origin"

Identify qualitative variables:

names(Auto)[!is_numeric_col]

[1] "name"

The above code doesn’t take into account the fact that some of these variables might actually be qualitative variables coded with numbers. For example origin is actually a qualitative variable coded with an integer from {1, 2, 3}. cylinders could be considered either quantitative or qualitative. Unlike origin, there is a clear ordering of the cylinders variable, so it will be useful to treat it as a factor for plots. For now we will treat it as quantitative.

Update origin to be a factor:

Auto <- Auto %>% 
  mutate(origin = factor(origin))

is_numeric_col <- map_lgl(Auto, is.numeric)
names(Auto)[is_numeric_col]
[1] "mpg"          "cylinders"    "displacement" "horsepower"   "weight"       "acceleration" "year"

Pairs plots:

Scatter plots

weight and mpg

ggplot(Auto) +
  geom_point(aes(weight, mpg))

weight and mpg facetted by cylinders

Auto %>% 
  mutate(cylinders = factor(cylinders)) %>% 
  filter(cylinders != 3, cylinders != 5) %>% 
  ggplot() +
    geom_point(aes(weight, mpg, color = cylinders)) +
    facet_wrap( ~ cylinders) +
    scale_color_brewer(palette = "Dark2")

weight and mpg facetted by cylinders with highlighting:

Auto %>% 
  mutate(cylinders = factor(cylinders)) %>% 
  filter(cylinders != 3, cylinders != 5) %>% 
  ggplot(aes(weight, mpg)) +
    geom_point(data = select(Auto, -cylinders), color = "grey70") +
    geom_point(aes(color = cylinders)) +
    facet_wrap( ~ cylinders) +
    scale_color_brewer(palette = "Dark2")

Boxplots

cylinders and mpg:

Auto %>% 
  mutate(cylinders = factor(cylinders)) %>% 
  filter(cylinders != 3, cylinders != 5) %>% 
  ggplot() +
    geom_boxplot(aes(cylinders, mpg, fill = cylinders),
                 show.legend = FALSE)

cylinders and mpg:

Auto %>% 
  mutate(cylinders = factor(cylinders)) %>% 
  filter(cylinders != 3, cylinders != 5) %>% 
  ggplot() +
    geom_boxplot(aes(cylinders, horsepower, fill = cylinders),
                 show.legend = FALSE)

  (f)

Based on the above exploratory plots it appears that cylinders and weight are look to be associated with mpg. For cylinders, cars with more cylinders tend to have lower mpg. For weight, heavier cars have lower mpg. From the pairs plot it looks like year is also associated with mpg. A scatterplot shows that newer cars tend to have lower mpg:

ggplot(Auto) +
  geom_jitter(aes(year, mpg))
